WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.000
Um, so we've been really interested in targeting the 9P amplicon, and as everyone knows, this

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:08.040
leads to upregulation of PD-L1 and 2.

00:00:08.240 --> 00:00:14.080
It also leads to upregulation of JAK1 and 2, which then also contributes to PD-L1 and

00:00:14.080 --> 00:00:14.660
2 expression.

00:00:14.860 --> 00:00:20.100
So it's kind of like a positive feedback loop within the 9P amplicon, and this leads to

00:00:20.100 --> 00:00:22.620
both increased proliferation and immune evasion.

00:00:22.620 --> 00:00:30.940
And as you know, 9P is amplified, you know, hallmark in Hodgkin lymphoma, highly in primary

00:00:30.940 --> 00:00:33.760
mediastinal, and a little less so in the pre-surgery cell lymphoma.

00:00:34.900 --> 00:00:41.520
Very closely accompanying 9P amplification is rearrangements in 16P, and this leads to

00:00:41.520 --> 00:00:48.040
loss of CT2A, which leads to decreased MHC expression, and then further sort of allows

00:00:48.040 --> 00:00:50.460
for an immune privilege phenotype.

00:00:50.460 --> 00:00:52.460
So we're interested in trying to sort of...

00:00:52.620 --> 00:00:54.780
target both of these derangements.

00:00:56.040 --> 00:01:01.620
This work was led by one of my mentees, Siddharth Tolu, who's now an assistant professor at

00:01:01.620 --> 00:01:06.300
Columbia University, and her hypothesis was that perhaps dual targeting of 9P amplicon

00:01:06.300 --> 00:01:11.940
with JAK/SAT inhibitor ruxolitinib and immune checkpoint blockade pembrolizumab will

00:01:11.940 --> 00:01:16.800
enhance immunogenicity, modulate lymphomagenesis, and induce cell death.

00:01:19.380 --> 00:01:22.020
So we looked at JAK inhibition across...

00:01:22.620 --> 00:01:27.920
a panel of lymphoma cell lines enriched in 9P amplification, found that there was a nice

00:01:30.180 --> 00:01:33.860
viability curve, cytotoxicity curve, and that there was a little bit more sensitivity in the

00:01:33.860 --> 00:01:35.940
9P amplified lymphomas.

00:01:37.220 --> 00:01:44.580
We looked at drivers of immunogenicity and cell growth and found that ruxolitinib led to

00:01:45.080 --> 00:01:53.500
increased CT2A expression, decreased PD-L1 and 2 expression, and decreased MYC expression.

00:01:53.500 --> 00:01:58.140
And these were most pronounced in those with a sort of higher 9P amplification.

00:02:00.140 --> 00:02:06.640
Looking at RNA sequencing, we found a number of modulated genes, and specifically we found decreased

00:02:06.640 --> 00:02:13.880
stat RNA sequencing, decreased MYC, and also decreased PD-L1 and 2.

00:02:15.080 --> 00:02:20.140
We also found that there was increased MHC-2 expression across the board, more or less.

00:02:21.200 --> 00:02:29.440
And looking at the profiles, we found that they were upregulated genes in lymphocyte differentiation,

00:02:29.440 --> 00:02:35.200
immune response, as well as response to type 1 interferon.

00:02:36.440 --> 00:02:39.960
And so with that, we were interested in looking at what was going on in the peripheral milieu.

00:02:40.200 --> 00:02:43.980
So we collected peripheral blood from Hodgkin and primary mediastinal patients,

00:02:44.360 --> 00:02:48.880
treated them ex vivo with ruxolitinib, and also pembrolizumab and the combination,

00:02:48.880 --> 00:02:55.120
and found that we were able to increase, so these are blood without any lymphoma within them,

00:02:55.180 --> 00:02:58.460
or are curious what was happening in the peripheral blood, and found that it increased

00:02:58.460 --> 00:03:05.580
encased T cells, decreased Tregs, and decreased PD-L1 expression in both CD4 and CD8 T cells.

00:03:06.900 --> 00:03:09.320
We then decided to create...

00:03:09.320 --> 00:03:15.040
We then decided to create lymphoma organoids or spheroids using a 9P amplified cell lines.

00:03:15.240 --> 00:03:20.780
Then we co-cultured these with healthy CD8 T cells, and we exposed them to both ruxolitinib,

00:03:20.780 --> 00:03:27.220
pembrolizumab, or the combination, to see how these impacted both cell kill and T cell infiltration.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:35.380
And so looking first just at these organoids or spheroids treated with ruxolitinib alone,

00:03:35.800 --> 00:03:38.780
hopefully it projects somewhat okay, but in the...

00:03:39.320 --> 00:03:43.560
The green are the live lymphoma cells, and the red represents the dead cells,

00:03:43.560 --> 00:03:48.360
and you can see sort of like a dose response with ruxolitinib, and you can really see in the 2.5

00:03:48.360 --> 00:03:56.220
microliter, micromolar concentration that there's really increased cell kill with ruxolitinib.

00:03:56.840 --> 00:03:59.880
Then when we add T cells, we don't really see that much of a change,

00:04:00.380 --> 00:04:07.440
but when we pretreat T cells with pembrolizumab and the organoids with ruxolitinib, we find that

00:04:07.440 --> 00:04:09.300
there's really robust cell kill.

00:04:09.320 --> 00:04:16.440
We then wanted to see how T cells were infiltrating within the organoid, and so this is...

00:04:16.440 --> 00:04:23.260
Here, the green, again, is the live cells, and the purple is the CD3 positive T cells.

00:04:24.080 --> 00:04:29.660
And we found when we added pembrolizumab to the T cells, you see, you know, nice infiltration

00:04:29.660 --> 00:04:35.780
to the organoid, but when we combine this with ruxolitinib, we really see intense infiltration

00:04:35.780 --> 00:04:36.560
of the spheroid.

00:04:38.240 --> 00:04:39.300
So again, we wanted to see how T cells were infiltrating within the organoid, and so this is

00:04:39.320 --> 00:04:41.620
we wanted to look what was happening in vivo.

00:04:42.280 --> 00:04:49.940
We used partially matched humanized mouse and grafted with carpus, a 9P amplified lymphoma cell

00:04:49.940 --> 00:04:56.780
line, and we found in mice treated, in the peripheral blood, again, in the combination,

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:04.880
there was reduced Tregs, increased activation of CD4 cells, CD4 T cells with CD4 ligand and CD69.

00:05:05.520 --> 00:05:08.880
We looked also in an immune...

00:05:09.320 --> 00:05:16.740
A competent mouse model engrafted with a lymphoma mouse cell line, and again, after treatment

00:05:16.740 --> 00:05:22.320
with the combination, we found, again, decreased Tregs, also decreased MDSCs and increased

00:05:22.320 --> 00:05:23.160
NK cells.

00:05:23.540 --> 00:05:32.220
We found increased activation of CD4 T cells with CD25 and CD44, and decreased exhaustion

00:05:32.220 --> 00:05:38.840
with decreased LAG3 and decreased PD-L1, and similar findings in the CD8 T cell population.

00:05:39.320 --> 00:05:47.920
When we combined ruxolitinib and pembrolizumab in this immune-competent mouse model, we found

00:05:47.920 --> 00:05:52.760
really prolonged overall survival and decreased growth with the combination.

00:05:54.320 --> 00:05:58.900
So using the humanized mouse, we performed single-cell RNA sequencing to try to get a

00:05:58.900 --> 00:06:01.920
better idea of what was going on within the tumor microenvironment.

00:06:02.140 --> 00:06:07.100
We were able to detect different types of cell types within the tumor, sort of different

00:06:07.100 --> 00:06:08.100
B-cell cell types.

00:06:09.320 --> 00:06:11.860
We were able to detect different types of cell types as well as stromal cells and T-cells.

00:06:12.680 --> 00:06:17.700
And we found this a little small, but we found that there was really increased T-cell infiltration

00:06:17.700 --> 00:06:21.160
with pembrolizumab and perhaps as well with the combination.

00:06:21.860 --> 00:06:29.300
And interestingly, the tumor had decreased MDSCs, increased activation of CD3-positive

00:06:29.300 --> 00:06:32.420
T cells within the tumor compartment.

00:06:33.960 --> 00:06:39.300
So sometimes we think of ruxolitinib as perhaps a way to reduce CD3-positive T cells, but

00:06:39.320 --> 00:06:39.460
it's not.

00:06:39.460 --> 00:06:39.500
It's not.

00:06:39.500 --> 00:06:39.560
It's not.

00:06:39.560 --> 00:06:39.580
It's not.

00:06:39.580 --> 00:06:39.600
It's not.

00:06:39.600 --> 00:06:39.620
It's not.

00:06:39.620 --> 00:06:39.660
It's not.

00:06:39.660 --> 00:06:39.680
It's not.

00:06:39.680 --> 00:06:39.720
It's not.

00:06:39.720 --> 00:06:39.740
It's not.

00:06:39.740 --> 00:06:39.760
It's not.

00:06:39.760 --> 00:06:39.800
It's not.

00:06:39.800 --> 00:06:39.820
It's not.

00:06:39.820 --> 00:06:39.920
It's not.

00:06:39.920 --> 00:06:39.980
It's not.

00:06:39.980 --> 00:06:40.000
It's not.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:40.040
It's not.

00:06:40.040 --> 00:06:40.080
It's not.

00:06:40.080 --> 00:06:40.380
It's not.

00:06:40.380 --> 00:06:40.420
It's not.

00:06:40.420 --> 00:06:40.440
It's not.

00:06:40.440 --> 00:06:40.460
It's not.

00:06:40.460 --> 00:06:47.640
Here we found that in certain types of contacts, ruxolitinib can increase immunogenicity

00:06:47.640 --> 00:06:52.880
in lymphoma cells by increasing the CT2A and MHC2 and suppress PD-L1 and 2.

00:06:53.300 --> 00:07:00.740
It decreased MYC-driven growth and it primed peripheral blood for increased NK cells,

00:07:00.900 --> 00:07:03.780
decreased Tregs, and decreased MDSCs.

00:07:03.780 --> 00:07:11.480
The combination enhanced organoid apoptosis and T cell infiltration, and it modulated

00:07:11.480 --> 00:07:14.460
the tumor microenvironment with increased T cell activation in vivo.

00:07:15.140 --> 00:07:18.300
The combination also led to prolonged survival in mice.

00:07:19.060 --> 00:07:22.860
So with that, we've developed a clinical trial, which is now open, and we're hoping

00:07:22.860 --> 00:07:24.700
to open it at collaborating sites.

00:07:24.840 --> 00:07:26.840
Some of the folks are here.

00:07:27.660 --> 00:07:31.900
There has been a clinical study looking at Ruxo plus Nevo and Hodgkin lymphoma.

00:07:31.900 --> 00:07:33.760
So we only have really an exploratory arm.

00:07:33.780 --> 00:07:39.120
In that cohort, really to try to look at this biology, we're staggering ruxolitinib

00:07:39.120 --> 00:07:44.200
and pembrolizumab and collecting samples along the way to try to better understand what's

00:07:44.200 --> 00:07:46.580
happening in the peripheral blood, as well as in the tumors.

00:07:47.080 --> 00:07:52.820
And then given our interest in sort of these pathways in T cell lymphomas, there's been

00:07:52.820 --> 00:07:58.080
a lot of interest in Jaxa inhibition in T cell lymphoma, as well as immune checkpoint

00:07:58.080 --> 00:07:58.700
blockade.

00:07:58.700 --> 00:08:03.620
We have two cohorts in both nodal PTCL and CTCL.

00:08:03.780 --> 00:08:08.420
And in the CTCL patients, we're collecting paired samples along the way in the skin.

00:08:08.420 --> 00:08:12.080
So we'll be really excited to see what's happening in the tumor microenvironment there.

00:08:13.080 --> 00:08:17.320
So with that, I thank you for listening and really want to acknowledge Sadat Tolu, who

00:08:17.320 --> 00:08:23.260
did the bulk of this work, and Ted Prochinski in my lab, our clinical team, and our grand

00:08:23.260 --> 00:08:24.080
support and collaborators.

00:08:24.400 --> 00:08:24.760
Thank you.
